# PE Physics Engine fork

This repository is a fork of the PE (Physics Engine) project. The original
project record is available through FAU CRIS:

https://cris.fau.de/projects/213447149/

This fork keeps the original rigid-body simulation core and adds current work
around triangle meshes, CGAL-backed geometry operations, DistanceMap-accelerated
collision queries, and interface tests.

## Requirements

Required:

- CMake >= 3.15
- Boost >= 1.68, including thread, system, filesystem, program_options, and random

Optional:

- Eigen, enabled by default
- nlohmann/json, enabled by default when available
- CGAL, needed for DistanceMap and CGAL mesh examples
- MPI, for distributed examples
- Irrlicht, for visualization examples
- OpenCL, for GPGPU support
- Doxygen and Graphviz, for generated documentation

## Building

CMake is the recommended build path:

```bash
mkdir build
cd build
cmake -G "Unix Makefiles" -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DLIBRARY_TYPE=STATIC ..
make
```

Common CMake options:

- `-DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release|Debug|RelWithDebInfo|MinSizeRel`
- `-DLIBRARY_TYPE=STATIC|SHARED|BOTH`
- `-DEXAMPLES=ON|OFF`
- `-DPE_BUILD_INTERFACE_TESTS=ON|OFF`
- `-DEIGEN=ON|OFF`
- `-DUSE_JSON=ON|OFF`
- `-DCGAL=ON|OFF`
- `-DMPI=ON|OFF`
- `-DIRRLICHT=ON|OFF`
- `-DOPENCL=ON|OFF`
- `-DBLAS=ON|OFF`

For example, to build the examples and CGAL/DistanceMap support:

```bash
mkdir build-cgal
cd build-cgal
cmake -G "Unix Makefiles" -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DEXAMPLES=ON -DCGAL=ON ..
make
```

The legacy `./configure` build still exists for compatibility with older PE
workflows. New development should prefer CMake.

## Running Examples

Example binaries are generated under the build tree when `-DEXAMPLES=ON` is
enabled. Typical runs:

```bash
./build/examples/boxstack/boxstack
mpirun -np 4 ./build/examples/mpicube/mpicube
```

CGAL and DistanceMap examples are in `examples/cgal_examples`:

```bash
./build/examples/cgal_examples/mesh_collision_test reference.obj output test_sphere.obj
./build/examples/cgal_examples/mesh_simulation --mesh1 mesh1.obj --mesh2 mesh2.obj
```

`mesh_simulation` also supports pose controls such as `--mesh2-position` and
`--mesh2-euler`, which are useful when reproducing mesh collisions.

## DistanceMap and CGAL

DistanceMap acceleration is integrated into the fine collision detection path for
triangle meshes. It is available when the project is built with `-DCGAL=ON`.

The main entry point is:

```cpp
#include <pe/core/detection/fine/DistanceMap.h>

TriangleMeshID mesh = createTriangleMesh(id, position, "mesh.obj", material, false, true);
mesh->enableDistanceMapAcceleration(resolution, tolerance);
```

DistanceMap queries are performed in the local mesh coordinate system and
transformed back into world coordinates for collision response. Related
implementation and examples live in:

- `pe/core/detection/fine/DistanceMap.h`
- `src/core/detection/fine/DistanceMap.cpp`
- `pe/core/detection/fine/MaxContacts.h`
- `examples/cgal_examples/`

## Tests

Interface smoke tests can be enabled through CMake:

```bash
mkdir build-interface-tests
cd build-interface-tests
cmake -G "Unix Makefiles" -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DPE_BUILD_INTERFACE_TESTS=ON ..
make
ctest --output-on-failure
```

Additional project-specific validation notes are kept in `tests/interface`.

## Documentation

The `doc` directory contains two kinds of documentation:

- Markdown technical notes under `doc/technical-notes`, such as
  `technical-overview.md`, `distance-map-implementation.md`, and
  `new-collision-system-implementation-guide.md`. These explain architecture,
  design decisions, algorithms, and implementation context beyond what is
  visible from the API alone.
- Legacy API documentation material, including `Doxyfile` and the image assets
  under `doc/pics`, used by the original Doxygen-based documentation flow.

Keeping these as separate documentation layers is intentional: the Markdown
files are the best starting point for understanding the current fork, while the
legacy API documentation remains useful as reference material for the original
engine interfaces.

## Repository Layout

- `pe/`: public headers and core library interfaces
- `src/`: library implementation files
- `examples/`: serial, MPI, mesh, CGAL, and visualization examples
- `tests/`: interface and utility tests
- `doc/technical-notes/`: current Markdown technical notes
- `doc/`: legacy API documentation config and assets
- `tutorial/`: legacy PE tutorial material
